page.text: This study analyzes US 20 from Section 3.26 to 4.41. This section of road appears on ODOT's
2009 listing of high crash locations (HSP Non‐Freeway), and it is rated #130 in the State. The
purpose of this report is to study this location and analyze the crashes to determine what, if
any, actions can be taken to reduce the high percentage of rear‐end, angle and left‐turn crashes
that occur in the study area.
This approximately 1.15‐mile section of US 20 is located in the City of Willoughby in Lake
County, Ohio. It is part of the urban state highway system under the jurisdiction of District 12 of
the Ohio Department of Transportation (ODOT). The section under study, log point 3.26 to 4.41,
begins at the intersection of US 20 (Euclid Ave.) and SR 91 (Som Center Rd.) and extends in an
easterly direction to just east of the intersection of US 20 and Shankland Rd. Based on
information supplied by District 12, LAK‐20 (3.26‐4.41) was ranked #130 on the 2009 HCLIS.
The safety problems identified at this location are as follows:
 Lack of access management – access points are too numerous and too closely‐spaced.

BPS staff conducted a field review on February 17 and March 7, 2011. BPS staff observed the
study area section and collected information regarding the existing conditions. The section
under study, log point 3.26 to 4.41, begins at the intersection of US 20 (Euclid Ave.) and SR 91
(Som Center Rd.) and extends in an easterly direction to 0.02 mile east of the intersection of US
20 and Shankland Rd. This east‐west section of US 20 is located in the City of Willoughby, Lake
County, Ohio and varies from a five lane to a four lane to a three lane urban minor arterial. US
20 is locally named Euclid Ave. and is predominately flat and straight in the study area.
This section of US 20 contains 7 public and 5 private roadway intersections, listed below from
Please note the Fire Station (37000 Euclid Ave.) also has a traffic signal that is activated only
when needed for emergencies. There are 50 private access points in the study area. As a
result, the total number of access points equals 72 in the 1.15‐mile section of the study area ‐
or 1 access point every 84.3 feet. The pavement is in good condition – no noticeable cracking
or potholes were observed throughout the project area. The pavement markings were also in
good condition. There is no permitted on‐street parking along US 20 in the study area, and
street lighting is present throughout the length of the study area. Through the entire study
area there are 14 bus stops for Laketran along US 20 (both sides of the road), and there are
sidewalks along both sides of US 20, ranging from four to eight feet in width.
The study area is primarily commercial, including West Pointe Plaza and Willoughby Commons,
with a few multi‐family complexes and some public facilities. Public facilities include a police
station, YMCA, pool, fire station, tennis courts, and high school, and these facilities are all
located in proximity of each other at the eastern end of the project area. Single‐family
residential is located off of US 20 along the intersecting side roads to the south of US 20.
There is congestion on SR 20 and significant queuing at intersections that is not cleared during
the PM peak hours along this corridor. Specifically, traffic back‐ups were observed on Beidler
Rd. at its intersection with US 20 during the afternoon peak hour. Turning movement counts
and a capacity analysis should be performed to determine solutions.
A total of 242 crashes occurred over the three‐year period, from 2007‐2009 within the study
area. The crash rate per million vehicle miles traveled is 8.70. The crash summary data are
included in Appendix A, and an overview is shown below:
Crash reports from January 1, 2007 through December 31, 2009 were obtained. During this
three‐year period, a total of 241 crashes occurred within the study limits. Of the 241 crashes,
107 were rear end (44.2%), 54 were angle (22.3%), 32 were left turns (13.2%), and 30 were
sideswipe‐passing (12.4%), comprising 92.1% of the crashes. Of the remaining 19, seven were
sideswipe‐meeting, five were backing, four lost control of their vehicles, two involved
pedestrians, and one involved a bicycle. Forty‐six of the crashes (19%) involved injury, but none
were fatal. Of the 241 crashes in the study area, most occurred during the day (80.6%), on dry
pavement (71.9%), and under no adverse weather condition (80.2%). Figures 7 – 13 include the
crash diagrams which show the approximate location of the 2007‐2009 crashes in the study

text.b: Study Area‐Wide Crash Analysis Patterns & Conclusions

page.text: Most crashes in the study area occurred on US 20 westbound or eastbound after 11:00 am,
peaking between 2:00 pm and 5:00 pm, with very few late at night or early morning. This
pattern indicates that the morning rush hour is probably not contributing to the crashes but
that the lunch and afternoon/early evening rush hours do see an increase.
Most crashes were property damage only, occurred during the day and under dry roadway
conditions. Most crashes were at or near an intersection (58%) or driveway (23%) and were
rear‐end type crashes. There were also a number of angle, left‐turn and sideswipe‐passing type
crashes. These patterns are indicative of dense access points which result in frequent vehicle
stopping to accommodate decelerating vehicles turning into an access point and slow‐moving
vehicles pulling out of an access point. Also, most of the sideswipe‐passing crashes occurred in
the five‐lane section of the study area, which could be indicative of lanes that are too narrow or
poorly‐defined striping that separates the through lanes; however, upon investigation the
pavement markings are adequate and although the inside through lanes are only 10 feet wide,
the outside through lanes and center lane are 12 feet wide.

page.text: A four‐hour turning movement count (7‐9 AM & 4‐6 PM) was completed at US 20/SR 91
intersection on February 1, 2011. Based on the four hour volume count and the typical 24‐hour
variation of traffic on principal and minor arterials (from the ODOT’s hourly percent by roadway
type), the year 2009 ADT along US 20 is 22,100. By year 2030, a 17% growth rate is projected
based on NOACA’s Regional model. Please note that the SR 20/SR 91 intersection is under
construction and has some capacity reductions in place as a result. The construction project is
lengthening the two left turn lanes on the southbound approach, which may affect signal
timings as presented in this study.

Capacity is the volume of traffic that can pass through a roadway facility in a given amount of
time (vehicles/hour). The concept of Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative measure of the
operation of the traffic flow. LOS considers such factors as speed, travel time, freedom to
maneuver, traffic interruptions, driver inconvenience, safety and delay. For different
transportation facilities, the LOS is based on different measures of effectiveness.
Signalized intersections are measured for average control delay in seconds per vehicle. Control
delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move‐up time, stopped delay and final
deceleration delay. The delay measurement for vehicles at a signalized intersection is a
combination of driver discomfort, driver frustration and lost travel time.
The LOS rating system as described in the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual gives a value of A
through F to each type of roadway facility representing best to worst traffic conditions. When
designing for roadway improvements, it is desirable to accommodate design peak hour volumes
at a LOS C or D. The below summarizes the levels of service for signalized intersections:

page.text: For the remaining signalized intersections, it is recommended to upgrade all signal heads to LED
signal head with backplates with reflective strips, where still needed.
Narrowing and better defining access points would be way to introduce some minor
improvements through the study area. Incremental consolidation of access points,
implementation of cross‐access agreements, and construction of driveways that connect with
side roads instead of US 20 would also help with access management without substantial right‐
of‐way impacts and without being too costly. Restricting left turns out of high‐crash
unsignalized driveways, and eventually closing some of them, should reduce the driveway‐
located angle crashes. It is also recommended to upgrade all signal heads to LED signal head
with backplates with reflective strips, where still needed, and at the US 20/SR 91 some minor
adjustments to the signal timings and cross walk timings are also recommended.
A capacity analysis is recommended at the Beidler Rd./Lake West Medical Building driveway
intersection with US 20 to determine the causes and solutions to the back‐ups currently
experienced on Beidler Rd. in the southbound direction. Widening the side roads to allow for
an additional turn lane may be warranted.
A capacity analysis is also recommended for the four‐lane section of US 20 to determine if it
can function as three‐lane section with two through lanes and a center two‐way left turn lane.
This change will also allow for dedicated left turn lanes at the Willoughby Commons eastern
access road/Police Station driveway intersection, Hamann Parkway intersection, and Shankland
Rd. intersection, which should help address left turn crashes and rear‐end crashes that result
from traffic backing up behind left‐turning vehicles. If the analysis concludes that the three‐
lane section is insufficient to handle the traffic demand, widening at just the intersections to
install left turn lanes is recommended.
